  <page>
    <title>Apple I</title>
    <id>1344</id>
    <revision>
      <id>430243233</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-21T20:06:36Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <ip>124.197.19.137</ip>
      </contributor>
      <comment>grammar</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Infobox computer
| name                 = Apple I (Apple-1)
| image                = [[File:Apple I Computer.jpg|250px|Apple I computer]]
| type                 = [[Personal computer]]
| developer            = [[Apple Inc.|Apple Computer]]
| release date         = April 11, 1976
| discontinued         = September 30, 1977
| processor            = [[MOS Technology 6502|MOS 6502]] @ [[megahertz|1 MHz]]
| memory               = 4 [[kilobyte|KB]] standard&lt;br /&gt;expandable to 8 KB or 48 KB using expansion cards
| graphics             = 40&amp;times;24 characters, hardware-implemented scrolling
| price                = {{USD|666.66}}
}}

The '''Apple I''', also known as the '''Apple-1''', was an early [[personal computer]].  They were designed and [[Handicraft|hand-built]] by [[Steve Wozniak]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ioltechnology.co.za/article_page.php?iSectionId=2892&amp;iArticleId=3456594 IOL Technology - Co-founder tells his side of Apple story]{{Dead link|date=February 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6167297 NPR : A Chat with Computing Pioneer Steve Wozniak]&lt;/ref&gt; Wozniak's friend [[Steve Jobs]] had the idea of selling the computer. The Apple I was [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s first product, demonstrated in April 1976 at the [[Homebrew Computer Club]] in Palo Alto, California.

==History==
The Apple I went on sale in July 1976 at a price of {{USD|666.66}},&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/1606-2-5937610.html|title=Video: Wozniak: $666.66 seemed like a good idea|date=2005-11-07|publisher=CNET News|accessdate=2009-02-19}}&lt;/ref&gt; because Wozniak liked repeating digits&lt;ref name=&quot;iWoz&quot;&gt;[[Steve Wozniak|Wozniak, Steven]]: &quot;[[iWoz]]&quot;, page 180. [[W. W. Norton]], 2006. ISBN 978-0-393-06143-7&lt;/ref&gt; and because they originally sold it to a local shop for $500 and added a one-third markup. About 200 units were produced. Unlike other hobbyist computers of its day, which were sold as kits, the Apple I was a fully assembled circuit board containing about 60+ chips. However, to make a working computer, users still had to add a case, power supply transformers, power switch, ASCII keyboard, and composite video display. An optional board providing a cassette interface for storage was later released at a cost of $75.

[[File:Apple 1 Advertisement Oct 1976.jpg | thumb | left | Introductory advertisement for the Apple I Computer]]
The Apple I's built-in [[computer terminal]] circuitry was distinctive. All one needed was a [[Keyboard (computing)|keyboard]] and an inexpensive [[television set]]. Competing machines such as the [[Altair 8800]] generally were programmed with front-mounted toggle switches and used indicator lights (red [[light-emitting diode|LED]]s, most commonly) for output, and had to be extended with separate hardware to allow connection to a computer terminal or a [[ASR33|teletypewriter machine]]. This made the Apple I an innovative machine for its day. In April 1977 the price was dropped to $475.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.applefritter.com/node/2703 April 1977 Price List | Applefritter&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; It  continued to be sold through August 1977, despite the introduction of the [[Apple II]] in April 1977, which began shipping in June of that year.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.applefritter.com/node/2715 Bill of Sale | Applefritter&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; Apple  dropped the Apple I from its price list by October 1977, officially discontinuing it.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.applefritter.com/node/2707 October 1977 Price List | Applefritter&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; As Wozniak was the only person who could answer most customer support questions about the computer, the company offered Apple I owners discounts and trade-ins for Apple IIs to persuade them to return their computers, contributing to their scarcity.&lt;ref name=&quot;ah04&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://apple2history.org/history/ah04/ | title=The Apple II, cont. | accessdate=February 27, 2011 | work=Apple II History}}&lt;/ref&gt;

As of 2008, an estimated 40 to 50 Apple I computers are still known to exist, making it a very rare [[collectable|collector's item]]. An Apple I reportedly sold for $50,000 USD at auction in 1999, with another apparently selling in 2009 for $17,500; however, a more typical price for an Apple I is in the $14,000&amp;ndash;$16,000 range.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} In November 2009 the Apple I with serial number 82 was listed on eBay with a starting bid of $50,000 but it is unreported as to whether the computer was sold. However, in November 2010, this same Apple I (with serial number 82) sold for the equivalent of $US178,000 ($US213,600 including the 'buyer's premium') at Christie's auction house in London,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11825954 BBC News 24 November 2010 00:48]&lt;/ref&gt;, making it by far the highest price paid for this model to date, at {{GBP|133,250}} ($210,000). The high value of this particular example is likely due to the rare documents and packaging offered in the sale rather than the computer itself; namely (and amongst others) the original packaging (with the return label showing Steve Jobs' parents' address, the original Apple Computer Inc 'headquarters' being their garage), a personally typed and signed letter from Jobs (answering technical questions about the computer) and the original invoice showing 'Steven' as the salesman. The computer was brought to Turin University where it was used to run BASIC.

==Emulators, clones, and replicas==
A software-compatible clone of the Apple I ([[Replica 1]]) produced using modern components, was released in 2003 at a price of around $200.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.applefritter.com/briel replica I - the apple I(c) clone], retrieved 2009-08-15&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.brielcomputers.com/wordpress/?cat=4 replica I] at official Briel computers web site, retrieved 2008-08-15&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Gagne, Ken [http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9136257/Image_gallery_Building_an_Apple_1_replica_from_scratch Image gallery: Building an Apple-1 replica from scratch], ''[[Computerworld]]'', 2009-08-14, story with pictures for assembling a Briel replica I from a kit, retrieved 2009-08-15&lt;/ref&gt; Other replicas and do-it-yourself kits and instructions are available.&lt;ref&gt;Owad, Tom ''[http://www.applefritter.com/replica Apple I Replica Creation]'', retrieved 2009-08-15&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.sbprojects.com/projects/apple1/ A-one], retrieved 2009-08-15&lt;/ref&gt;

The [[Multi Emulator Super System]] emulator also supports the Apple I.&lt;ref&gt;[http://mess.redump.net/mess:drivers:apple1:apple1 Apple I], retrieved 2008-08-15&lt;/ref&gt;

