  <page>
    <title>Apatosaurus</title>
    <id>1346</id>
    <revision>
      <id>428403922</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-10T11:18:20Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>FunkMonk</username>
        <id>4280259</id>
      </contributor>
      <comment>/* In popular culture */</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">&lt;!--{{About|the sauropod dinosaur formerly called Apatosaurus|for other uses|Brontosaurus (disambiguation)}}--&gt;
{{Automatic taxobox
| fossil_range = [[Late Jurassic]], {{Geological range|154|150}}
| image = Louisae.jpg
| image_caption = Mounted skeleton of ''A. louisae'', [[Carnegie Museum]]
| image_width = 300px
| authority = [[Othniel Charles Marsh|Marsh]], 1877
| subdivision = {{bold species list
|{{extinct}}A. ajax|Marsh, 1877 ([[Type (zoology)|type]])
|{{extinct}}A. excelsus|(Marsh, 1879) [originally ''Brontosaurus'']
|{{extinct}}A. louisae|Holland, 1915
|{{extinct}}A. parvus|(Peterson &amp; Gilmore, 1902)&lt;br /&gt; [originally ''Elosaurus'']}}
| synonyms = {{species list
|Brontosaurus|Marsh, 1879
|Elosaurus|Peterson &amp; Gilmore, 1902}}
}}
'''''Apatosaurus''''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|ə|ˌ|p|æ|t|ɵ|ˈ|s|ɔr|ə|s}}), also known by the popular but scientifically redundant [[synonym (taxonomy)|synonym]] '''''Brontosaurus''''', is a [[genus]] of [[sauropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived from about 154 to 150 million years ago, during the [[Jurassic]] [[Period (geology)|Period]] ([[Kimmeridgian]] and early [[Tithonian]] ages).&lt;ref name=turner1999/&gt; It was one of the largest land [[animal]]s that ever existed, with an average length of {{convert|23|m|ft|abbr=on}} and a mass of at least {{convert|23|MT|ST}}. The composite term ''Apatosaurus'' comes from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] names ''apate'' ({{Polytonic|ἀπάτη}})/''apatelos'' ({{Polytonic|ἀπατηλός}}) meaning &quot;deception&quot;/&quot;deceptive&quot; and ''sauros'' ({{Polytonic|[[wikt:σαῦρος|σαῦρος]]}}) meaning &quot;lizard&quot;; thus, &quot;deceptive lizard&quot;. [[Othniel Charles Marsh]] gave it this name because he regarded the [[Chevron (anatomy)|chevron bones]] as similar to those of some [[mosasaur]]s, members of a group of prehistoric marine lizards.

The cervical vertebrae were less elongated and more heavily constructed than those of ''[[Diplodocus]]'' and the bones of the leg were much stockier (despite being longer), implying a more robust animal. The tail was held above the ground during normal locomotion. Like most sauropods, ''Apatosaurus'' had only a single large claw on each forelimb, with the first three toes on the hind limb possessing claws.

[[Fossil]]s of these animals have been found in [[Bone Cabin Quarry#Nine Mile Quarry|Nine Mile Quarry]] and [[Bone Cabin Quarry]] in [[Wyoming]] and at sites in [[Colorado]], [[Oklahoma]] and [[Utah]], present in stratigraphic zones 2-6.&lt;ref name=&quot;foster-appendix&quot;&gt;Foster, J. (2007). &quot;Appendix.&quot; ''Jurassic West: The Dinosaurs of the Morrison Formation and Their World''. Indiana University Press. pp. 327-329.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Description==
[[File:Apatosaurus scale mmartyniuk wiki.png|thumb|left|Comparison of three species and a human: ''A. louisae'' (red), ''A. excelsus'' (violet), and ''A. ajax'' (green)]]
''Apatosaurus'' was a large, long-necked [[quadruped]]al animal with a long, whip-like tail. Its forelimbs were slightly shorter than its hindlimbs. One measurement places the total length of the species ''Apatosaurus louisae'' at {{convert|22|m|ft|abbr=on}}.&lt;ref name=&quot;mazzettaetal2004&quot;&gt;Mazzetta, G.V., Christiansen, P., and Farina, R.A. (2004). [http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/tmp/papers/Mazzetta-et-al_04_SA-dino-body-size.pdf &quot;Giants and bizarres: body size of some southern South American Cretaceous dinosaurs.&quot;] ''Historical Biology'', '''2004''': 1-13.&lt;/ref&gt;

It was roughly the weight of four elephants.&lt;ref name=&quot;Holtz2008&quot;&gt;Holtz, Thomas R. Jr. (2008) ''Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages'' [http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/DinoappendixSummer2008.pdf Supplementary Information]&lt;/ref&gt; One specimen of ''A. excelsus'' was estimated to weigh {{convert|25952|kg|lb|abbr=on}};&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal| last1=Erickson | first1=Gregory M.| last2=Curry Rogers | first2=Kristina |last3 =Yerby|first3=Scott A.| title=Dinosaurian growth patterns and rapid avian growth rates. | journal=Nature | year= 2001 | volume= 412| pmid=11473315 | issue= 6845 | pages= 429–33 | doi=10.1038/35086558 }}&lt;/ref&gt; estimates for ''A. louisae'' were {{convert|20600|kg|lb|abbr=on}}&lt;ref name=&quot;mazzettaetal2004&quot;/&gt; and {{convert|22407|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.&lt;ref name=Seebacher01&gt;{{Cite journal| last1 = Seebacher | first1 =  Frank | title = A new method to calculate allometric length-mass relationships of dinosaurs | journal = Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology | volume = 21 | pages = 51–52 | year = 2001 | doi = 10.1671/0272-4634(2001)021[0051:ANMTCA]2.0.CO;2}}&lt;/ref&gt; Other estimates of the body mass of adult ''Apatosaurus'' species range from {{convert|18000|kg|lb|abbr=on}}&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal| last1=Packard | first1=G.C.| last2=Boardman | first2=T.J. |last3 =Birchard|first3=G.F.| year= 2009 |title= Allometric equations for predicting body mass of dinosaurs |journal= Journal of Zoology |volume=279 |pages=102–110 | doi= 10.1111/j.1469-7998.2009.00594.x }}&lt;/ref&gt; to {{convert|35000|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.&lt;ref name=Seebacher01/&gt; A microscopic study of ''Apatosaurus'' bones concluded that the animals grew rapidly when young and reached near-adult sizes in about 10 years.&lt;ref name=Curry99&gt;{{Cite journal|doi= 10.1080/02724634.1999.10011179 |last= Curry |first= Kristina A. |authorlink = Kristina Curry Rogers |year= 1999|title= Ontogenetic histology of Apatosaurus (Dinosauria: Sauropoda): new insights on growth rates and longevity |journal= Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology |volume=19 |issue=4 |pages=654–665 | url= http://www.jstor.org/stable/4524036 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

The skull was small in comparison with the size of the animal. The jaws were lined with spatulate teeth, which resembled chisels, suited to an herbivorous diet. Like other sauropods, the vertebrae of the neck were deeply bifurcated; that is, they carried paired spines, creating a wide and deep profile for the neck.&lt;ref name=dinonathist&gt;Fasovsky, D.E. and Weishampel, D.B. (2009). ''Dinosaurs: A Concise Natural History''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. ISBN 978-0-521-88996-4&lt;/ref&gt; The apparently massive neck was, however, filled with an extensive system of weight-saving air sacs. ''Apatosaurus'', like its close relative ''[[Supersaurus]]'', is notable for the incredibly tall spines on its vertebrae, which make up more than half the height of the individual bones. Also unusual among diplodocids is the shape of the tail, which is comparatively thin in breadth and short in height, a profile caused by the vertebral spines decreasing in height rapidly the farther they are from the hips. ''Apatosaurus'' also had very long ribs compared to most other diplodocids, giving it an unusually deep chest. The limb bones were also very robust.&lt;ref name=LHW07&gt;{{Cite journal|last=Lovelace |first=David M. |coauthors=Hartman, Scott A.; and Wahl, William R. |year=2007 |title=Morphology of a specimen of ''Supersaurus'' (Dinosauria, Sauropoda) from the Morrison Formation of Wyoming, and a re-evaluation of diplodocid phylogeny |journal=Arquivos do Museu Nacional |volume=65 |issue=4 |pages=527–544 | url = http://server1.bhbfonline.org/Specimens/CLPV_II_Supersaurus.pdf}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Classification and species==
[[File:Brontosaurus skeleton 1880s.jpg|thumb|left|1896 diagram of the ''A. excelsus'' (then ''Brontosaurus'') skeleton by [[Othniel Charles Marsh|O.C. Marsh]]. The head is based on material now assigned to ''[[Brachiosaurus]] sp.''&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book
| url = http://books.google.com/?id=CLEPeg_SjTcC&amp;pg=PA69
| title = The Upper Jurassic Morrison Formation: an interdisciplinary study
| first1 = Kenneth | last1 = Carpenter | first2 = Virginia | last2 = Tidwell
| chapter = Preliminary Description of a Brachiosaurus Skull from Felch Quarry 1, Garden Park, Colorado
| editor1-first = Kenneth | editor1-last = Carpenter
| editor2-first = Dan | editor2-last = Chure
| editor3-first = James Ian | editor3-last = Kirkland
| publisher = Taylor &amp; Francis | year = 1998
| isbn = 978-90-5699-183-8
}}&lt;/ref&gt;]]
''Apatosaurus'' is a member of the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Diplodocidae]], a [[cladistics|clade]] of gigantic [[sauropod]] [[dinosaur]]s. The family includes some of the longest creatures ever to walk the earth, including ''[[Diplodocus]]'', ''[[Supersaurus]]'', ''[[Suuwassea]]'', and ''[[Barosaurus]]''. Within the subfamily Apatosaurinae, ''Apatosaurus'' may be most closely related to ''Suuwassea'', ''Supersaurus'' and ''[[Eobrontosaurus]]''.&lt;ref name=autogenerated1&gt;{{Cite journal|last=Lovelace |first=David M. |year=2007 |title=Morphology of a specimen of ''Supersaurus'' (Dinosauria, Sauropoda) from the Morrison Formation of Wyoming, and a re-evaluation of diplodocid phylogeny |journal=Arquivos do Museu Nacional |volume=65 |issue=4 |pages=527–544 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;taylornaish05&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal | author = Taylor, M.P. and Naish, D. | year = 2005 | title = The phylogenetic taxonomy of Diplodocoidea (Dinosauria: Sauropoda) | url = http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/pubs/ | journal = PaleoBios | volume = 25 | issue = 2 | pages = 1–7 | archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5msewSMAx | archivedate = 2010-01-18| deadurl=no}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;harris06&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1017/S1477201906001805 | author = Harris, J.D. | year = 2006 | title = The significance of ''Suuwassea emiliae'' (Dinosauria: Sauropoda) for flagellicaudatan intrarelationships and evolution | url =  | journal = Journal of Systematic Palaeontology | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages = 185–198 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 1877, [[Othniel Charles Marsh]] published the name of the [[type species]] ''Apatosaurus ajax''. He followed this in 1879 with a description of another, more complete specimen, which he thought represented a new [[genus]] and [[species]], which he named ''Brontosaurus excelsus''. In 1903, [[Elmer Riggs]] re-examined the fossils. While he agreed with Marsh that ''Brontosaurus excelsus'' was likely a distinct species, he also noted many similarities between ''B. excelsus'' and ''A. ajax'', and decided that both should be placed in the same genus. Riggs re-classified the species as ''Apatosaurus excelsus''.&lt;ref name=&quot;riggs-1903&quot;&gt;{{cite journal
|last=Riggs|first=Elmer|authorlink=Elmer S. Riggs
|year=1903
|title=Structure and Relationships of Opisthocoelian Dinosaurs. Part I, ''Apatosaurus'' Marsh
|journal=Publications of the Field Columbian Museum|volume=Geological Series|issue=2|pages=165–196
|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ssgPAAAAIAAJ&amp;printsec=frontcover
}}&lt;/ref&gt; Almost all paleontologists since Riggs published his opinions have agreed that the two species should be classified together in a single genus. According to the rules of the [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature|ICZN]] (which governs the scientific names of animals), the name ''Apatosaurus'', having been published first, had priority as the official name; ''Brontosaurus'' is considered a [[Synonym (taxonomy)|junior synonym]] and has therefore been discarded from formal use.

