'''Anbar''' ('''{{lang|ar|الأنبار}}''') was a town in [[Iraq]], at lat. 33 deg.  22' N., long. 43 deg.  49' E, on the east bank of the [[Euphrates]], just south of the Nahr 'Isa, or Sakhlawieh [[canal]], the northernmost of the canals connecting that river with the [[Tigris]].

==History==
Anbar was originally called '''Firuz Shapur''' ('''Firuz Shabur'''), or '''Perisapora''' and was founded circa [[350]] [[AD]] by [[Shapur II]], [[Sassanid Empire|Sassanid]] king of [[Persia]]. Perisapora was captured and destroyed by Emperor [[Julian the Apostate|Julian]] in [[363]], but speedily rebuilt.  The town became a refuge for the [[Arab]], [[Christianity|Christian]], and [[Jew]]ish colonies of that region.{{sfn|Peters|1911}} Anbar was adjacent or identical to the [[History of the Jews in Iraq#Babylonia as the center of Judaism (219 AD - ~1050 AD)|Babylonian Jewish]]  center of [[Nehardea]] (Hebrew: '''{{lang|he|נהרדעא}}'''), and lies a short distance from the present-day town of [[Fallujah]], formerly the [[History of the Jews in Iraq#Babylonia as the center of Judaism (219 AD - ~1050 AD)|Babylonian Jewish]] center of [[Pumbeditha]] ([[Hebrew]]: '''{{lang|he|פומבדיתא}}).

The name of the town was then changed to Anbar (&quot;[[granaries]]&quot;). [[As-Saffah|Abu al-Abbas as-Saffah]], the founder of the [[Abbasid]] caliphate, made it his capital, and such it remained until the founding of [[Baghdad]] in [[762]]. It continued to be a place of much importance throughout the Abbasid period.{{sfn|Peters|1911}}

==Today==
It is now it is entirely deserted, occupied only by ruin mounds. The great number of these indicates the former importance of the city.{{sfn|Peters|1911}}

== See also ==
*[[Nehardea]]
*[[Fallujah]]
*[[Pumbeditha]]

